<br>
Also, if a different camp opens you can move your group there. If someone needs a quest mob somewhere, ok lets go do it. Hell if you want just move the whole group to a different zone. In LDoN, however, you are stuck where you are until you finish the mission lest you lose those oh so precious points.<br>
<br>
I know you all think it is great that you are moving about instead of pulling to a wall, but each adventure camp seems to have 2 or 3 cookie cutter zones that are identical in feel and very similar in appearance with no real variation except where the dead ends are, you kill a bunch of weak ass trash mobs as fast as you can and once in a while kill some equally weak ass name who drops the same few craptastic loots every time. How goddamm saturated with those stupid arrow summoning  bags is the bazaar going to be in a month? Loot that anyone can get five times a day is not special no matter how nice it is. <br>
<br>
And WTF ever happened to CR's?? In a real dungeon crawl you stand a reasonable chance of wiping and being faced with getting your corpses from behind crowds of respawned mobs. This was a risk that made success seem sweeter. In LDoN you are competeing with a stop watch, and even if the stop watch wins, your corpses get spit out of the dungeon, thank you come again. Yes this started in PoP but at least there were respawns there, if you have no rezzer and one person dies, who cares just run back and help us beat the clock!<br>
<br>
I suppose if all you could ever find to do before was sit at a wall in PoV pulling stuff to kill, then you might find this shit exciting, OH NOZ! TEH TIMER IS RUNNING!!1!1, but I contend that if that was how you spent the bulk of your time in EQ, then maybe it was not game mechanics that were at fault but how YOU choose to make use of them and your sick desire to only do that which yields the highest pixel reward instead of mixing it up in terms of what how and where to pull and kill things. Granted, all this is coming from a guy who has probably spent over 100 hours running in circles around the same picnic table in Plane of Fire, but I would also pull casters, spawn named mobs to get loot drops for guildies, and welcome anyone of any class to come group with me and offer what ever they could while we shot the shit and got xp. People could go afk whenever they needed to and usually still get rewarded by a different pullers and support members while they did, I bet there were clerics who were happy to get some xp by standing around nuking while someone else did the work for a change. I bet most other servers saw this as a defined camp where one or two kite classes would sit around by themselves hoarding xp all day. <br>
<br>
I admit there are some cool new mob models in LDoN but that only goes so far in spicing up the same replicated set of tunnels and halls over and over again. Maybe I am crazy, bitter and/or jaded but this is how I feel. Everyone else seems to prefer having thier gaming experience spoon fed to them with little risk. I myself liked having the ability to let my own imagination direct some of what my gaming experience will be, with LDoN the game itself dictates your every move. <br>
<br>
